'''Seán Hoare''' (born 15 March 1994) is an Irish professional footballer playing for [[League of Ireland]] club [[Dundalk F.C.|Dundalk]].

==Career==

===St Patrick's Athletic===

====Under 19s====
Hoare signed with [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]]'s Under 19s in the summer of 2012. He signed on to the scholarship scheme between [[National University of Ireland, Maynooth|NUI Maynooth]] and [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]].<ref name="nuim">{{cite web|url=http://www.nuim.ie/study-maynooth/undergraduate-studies/scholarships/sport-scholarships|title=Sport Scholarships &#124; NUI Maynooth|publisher=nuim.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> Hoare's first involvement with the first team squad came on 1 October 2012 when he was an unused substitute in a 5–0 win over [[University College Dublin A.F.C.|UCD]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inform.fai.ie/Statsportal/Fixtures.aspx?fixtureID=vbaQQLm35cZtd11mQiuldw==&matchID=xAuOrF213oBZRdCA5lPlOA== |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140427222826/http://inform.fai.ie/Statsportal/Fixtures.aspx?fixtureID=vbaQQLm35cZtd11mQiuldw==&matchID=xAuOrF213oBZRdCA5lPlOA== |dead-url=yes |archive-date=27 April 2014 |accessdate=27 April 2014 }}</ref>

====2013 season====
Hoare made his first team debut on 4 June 2013 in a 2–0 [[Overtime (sports)|AET]] win over [[Longford Town F.C.|Longford Town]] in the [[2013 Leinster Senior Cup|Leinster Senior Cup Quarter Final]] at [[Richmond Park (football ground)|Richmond Park]].<ref name="extratime">{{cite web|url=http://www.extratime.ie/newsdesk/articles/10429/st-patricks-ath-2---0-longford-town/|title=St Patrick&#39;s Ath 2 – 0 Longford Town – Extratime.ie – League of Ireland|publisher=extratime.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> His next appearance was a [[Derbies in the League of Ireland|Dublin derby]] away to [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] in the quarter final of the [[League of Ireland Cup|League Cup]].<ref name="extratime2">{{cite web|url=http://extratime.ie/fixtures/detail/19696/2/|title=Shamrock Rovers v St. Patrick&#39;s Ath – Tallaght Stadium – Extratime.ie – League of Ireland Fixtures|publisher=extratime.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> Hoare also played in the [[2013 Leinster Senior Cup|Leinster Senior Cup Semi-final]] win away to [[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]]<ref name="extratime3">{{cite web|url=http://extratime.ie/fixtures/detail/19835/2/|title=Shelbourne v St. Patrick&#39;s Ath – Tolka Park – Extratime.ie – League of Ireland Fixtures|publisher=extratime.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> and also in the final at [[Richmond Park (football ground)|Richmond Park]] as Pats were runners up to [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]].<ref name="extratime4">{{cite web|url=http://extratime.ie/fixtures/detail/20194/2/|title=St. Patrick&#39;s Ath v Shamrock Rovers – Richmond Park – Extratime.ie – League of Ireland Fixtures|publisher=extratime.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> Although he didn't make any [[League of Ireland]] appearances, manager [[Liam Buckley]] ensured all players in the squad received winners medals, as the club lifted their ninth league title on 18 October 2013 against [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]].

====Collingwood Cup====
As part of the scholarship scheme between Pats and [[Maynooth University]] Hoare played for the university's football team as well as his club's under 19 side. [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]] captain [[Ger O'Brien]] was also appointed as manager of university's football side, with Pats goalkeeper [[Brendan Clarke]] brought in as his assistant before the annual football competition between universities and colleges the 2014 [[Collingwood Cup]]. [[Ger O'Brien|O'Brien]] organised a friendly against Pats' first team and Hoare impressed manager [[Liam Buckley]] as Maynooth lost 2–1.<ref name="nuim2">{{cite web|url=http://www.nuim.ie/student-services/news/nui-maynooth-take-st-patricks-athletic-fc|title=NUI Maynooth take on St Patrick&#039;s Athletic FC &#124; NUI Maynooth|publisher=nuim.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> Hoare was made captain of the college side and scored the winner as they knocked out tournament favourites [[University College Dublin A.F.C.|UCD]] in the quarter final by a 2–1 scoreline.<ref name="irishtimes">{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/maynooth-shock-holders-ucd-in-collingwood-cup-1.1705877|title=Maynooth shock holders UCD in Collingwood Cup – Soccer News &#124; Football Results, Fixtures & Tables &#124; The Irish Time – Thu, Feb 27, 2014|publisher=irishtimes.com|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> After knocking [[University College Cork A.F.C.|UCC]] in the semi-final, Hoare's Maynooth side would face [[National University of Ireland, Galway|NUI Galway]] in the final at the [[UCD Bowl]], which was broadcast live on [[Setanta Sports]]. Hoare captained his side to a 2–1 victory to win Maynooth's first ever Collingwood Cup and he was named as Player of the Tournament after the game.<ref name="fai">{{cite web|url=http://www.fai.ie/domestic-a-grassroots/third-level-football/103787-nui-maynooth-claims-collingwood-cup.html|title=Football Association of Ireland – NUI Maynooth claims Collingwood Cup|publisher=fai.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>

====2014 season====
Hoare was involved in the first team's pre-season training for the first time, in late January/early February 2014, taking part in the teams friendly games before playing in the [[Collingwood Cup]] with [[Maynooth University]]. Hoare signed his first professional contract and was given the squad number 20 before the season started.<ref name="stpatsfc">{{cite web|url=http://stpatsfc.com/news.php?id=5974#.U11fKDK9KSM|title=Club News : Saints' 2014 Squad No's!|publisher=stpatsfc.com|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> His first appearance of the season was a 2–0 defeat to [[Sligo Rovers F.C.|Sligo Rovers]].<ref name="extratime5">{{cite web|url=http://www.extratime.ie/fixtures/detail/26635/2/|title=Sligo Rovers v St. Patrick&#39;s Ath – The Showgrounds – Extratime.ie – League of Ireland Fixtures|publisher=extratime.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> On 28 March 2014, as Pats were away to [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]], [[Ken Oman]] picked up a groin injury in the 29th minute and was replaced by Hoare who was making his [[League of Ireland]] debut. He marked the previous season's top goalscorer [[Rory Patterson]] and contributed towards a clean sheet as the Saints drew 0–0. After a poor 4–1 defeat at home to [[Dundalk F.C.|Dundalk]], [[Derek Foran]] was replaced by Hoare for the away trip to [[Bray Wanderers A.F.C.|Bray Wanderers]]<ref name="extratime6">{{cite web|url=http://www.extratime.ie/fixtures/detail/20265/2/|title=Bray Wanderers v St. Patrick&#39;s Ath – Carlisle Grounds – Extratime.ie – League of Ireland Fixtures|publisher=extratime.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> and his performance was praised by both sets of supporters and the media after the game. Hoare maintained his place at [[centre back]] alongside Kenny Browne for the visit of [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] and put in a Man-of-the-match performance as Pats beat their arch rivals 1–0, earning Hoare huge praise from supporters on social media and making it into many website's Team of the Week section.<ref name="thejournal">{{cite web|url=http://thescore.thejournal.ie/airtricity-league-team-of-the-week-2-1414794-Apr2014/|title=Here's our SSE Airtricity League Premier Division Team of the Week|publisher=thescore.thejournal.ie|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> Following this performance, Hoare became a mainstay in the starting eleven alongside Browne, even when [[Ken Oman]] and Derek Foran return from injury, such was the defensive solidity of the Saints back five of [[Brendan Clarke]], [[Ger O'Brien]], Hoare, Browne and [[Ian Bermingham]]. On 30 May 2014, Hoare scored his first goal for Pats in a 5–2 win over [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]] at [[Richmond Park (football ground)|Richmond Park]], when he headed a [[Killian Brennan]] freekick into the top right corner in the 48th minute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://extratime.ie/fixtures/detail/20320/2/ |title=St. Patrick's Ath v Derry City – Richmond Park – Extratime.ie – League of Ireland Fixtures |website=Extratime.ie |date=30 May 2014 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Hoare picked up an ankle injury on 6 June in a 3–0 win over [[St. Patrick's C.Y.F.C.|St. Patrick's CY]] in the [[2014 FAI Cup|FAI Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://extratime.ie/fixtures/detail/132/2017/26697/2/ |title=St Patrick's CYFC v St. Patrick's Ath – Irishtown Stadium – Extratime.ie – League of Ireland Fixtures |website=Extratime.ie |date=6 June 2014 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> This injury would rule him out of the next six competitive games but Hoare made his comeback on 23 July when he came on from the bench to replace the injured [[Ger O'Brien]] at [[right back]] against [[Legia Warsaw]] in the [[2014–15 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], his debut in [[UEFA|European]] competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://extratime.ie/fixtures/detail/26785/2/ |title=St. Patrick's Ath v Legia Warsaw – Richmond Park – Extratime.ie – League of Ireland Fixtures |website=Extratime.ie |date=23 July 2014 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Hoare returned to the starting eleven three days later for the trip to [[Athlone Town A.F.C.|Athlone Town]] and helped his side to a clean sheet as well as scoring the second goal to secure a 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/irish-soccer-league/2014/0726/633307-athlone-town-v-st-pats-athletic/ |title=Pat's back on track with win in Athlone – RTÉ Sport |website=Rte.ie |date= |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> On 5 October 2014, Hoare scored in the [[2014 FAI Cup|FAI Cup Semi-final]] at home to [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]], when he headed home from a corner to restore Pats' lead in the 37th minute before they ran out 6–1 winners to book a place in the final at the [[Aviva Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/irish-soccer-league/2014/1005/650176-st-patricks-athletic-v-finn-harps/ |title=Pat's crush Harps to secure final berth – RTÉ Sport |website=Rte.ie |date= |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Hoare was a part of the starting eleven that wrote themselves into [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]] history by beating [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]] 2–0 to end the club's hoodoo by winning the [[FAI Cup]] for the first time in 53 years, on 2 November 2014 at the [[Aviva Stadium]] in front of a crowd of just over 17,000.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/national-league/st-patrick-s-athletic-end-fai-cup-hoodoo-with-win-over-derry-city-1.1985425 |title=St Patrick's Athletic end FAI Cup hoodoo with win over Derry City |website=Irishtimes.com |date=3 November 2014 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> As well as being called up to the [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland under-21s]], He was voted the [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]] Young Player of the Year following an excellent [[2014 St Patrick's Athletic F.C. season|2014 season]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://stpatsfc.com/news.php?id=6555#.VGsg54jfWrU |title=Club News : 2014 Awards Night Winners |website=Stpatsfc.com |date=15 November 2014 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> In November 2014, Hoare impressed on trial with [[Premier League]] side [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Daniel McDonnell |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/other-soccer/derby-and-celtic-join-race-for-prolific-eoin-doyle-30872553.html |title=Derby and Celtic join race for prolific Eoin Doyle |website=Independent.ie |date=31 December 2014 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>

====2015 season====
It was announced on 15 January 2015 that Hoare changed his squad number again, this time to first XI number, number 5.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://stpatsfc.com/news.php?id=6600#.VLhpS4HfWrU |title=Club News : 2015 Squad No's Announced |website=Stpatsfc.com |date=15 January 2015 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Amidst from interest in Hoare from such English clubs as [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|MK Dons]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], [[St Patrick's Athletic F.C.|St Patrick's Athletic]] held onto their man as the English transfer window closed on 2 February. Hoare was given the honour of captaining the [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland under-21s]] against the [[Football Association of Ireland|Republic of Ireland Amateur International's]] on 21 February 2015.<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url=http://www.fai.ie/ireland/news/king-names-home-based-u21-squad-for-training-game |title=King names home-based U21 squad for Training game &#124; Football Association of Ireland |website=Fai.ie |date= |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> He made his first [[President of Ireland's Cup|President's Cup]] appearance on 28 February as the Saints finished runners up following a 2–1 loss to [[Dundalk F.C.|Dundalk]] at [[Oriel Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stpatsfc.com/report.php?report=668 |title=Match Report |publisher=stpatsfc.com |date=28 February 2015 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> Hoare went on to feature in St Pats' [[League of Ireland Cup|League Cup]] success, beating [[Galway United]] on penalties in the final.<ref>http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/league-of-ireland/st-patricks-athletic-crowned-ea-sports-cup-champions-after-penalty-drama-31541571.html</ref>

====2016 season====
The [[2016 St Patrick's Athletic F.C. season|2016 season]] was a disappointing one for St Pat's and Hoare, as they disappointingly failed to secure qualification for Europe for the first time since 2009. However they did retain the [[League of Ireland Cup|League Cup]], with Hoare playing the full 90 minutes in a 4-1 win over [[Limerick F.C.|Limerick]] in the final.<ref>http://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2016/0917/817221-limerick-fc-v-st-pats-athletic/</ref> He also featured in all four of the Saints' [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] qualifiers, as they knocked out [[Jeunesse Esch]] of [[Luxembourg]], before being narrowly beaten by [[FC Dinamo Minsk|Dinamo Minsk]] of [[Belarus]].

==International career==
Hoare was called up to the [[Republic of Ireland national under-21 football team|Republic of Ireland under-21]] team for the first time, on 5 November 2014 by manager [[Noel King]] for the friendlies against [[United States men's national under-21 soccer team|United States under-21]] and [[Russia national under-21 football team|Russia under-21]], following an excellent debut season in the [[League of Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fai.ie/ireland/news/king-announces-u21-squad-for-usa-russia-games |title=King announces U21 squad for USA & Russia games &#124; Football Association of Ireland |website=Fai.ie |date= |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> He made his debut for the under-21s on 17 November 2014 when he came on as a substitute in the 73rd minute against [[Russia national under-21 football team|Russia under-21]] in a 2–2 draw at the [[Marbella]] football centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fai.ie/ireland/match/55502/2015/999941232?tab=report |title=Russia 2 - 2 Republic of Ireland &#124; 2015 - Under-21 Friendlies &#124; 999941232 &#124; Football Association of Ireland |website=Fai.ie |date=17 November 2014 |accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> His second appearance came on 21 February 2015 when he captained the side against the [[Football Association of Ireland|Republic of Ireland Amateur International's]].<ref name="autogenerated1"/>

